article.headline: Oregon State 67, Arizona State 59
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Even as they lost their first four Pac-10 games, the Oregon State Beavers thought they were better than their record. They finally produced some evidence Saturday, rallying from an eight-point second half deficit to defeat Arizona State 67-59 and snap a four-game losing streak. "It feels good to get that monkey off our back," said forward Sasa Cuic, who led all scorers with 20 points. "We've been practicing hard the whole time. We've heard a lot of criticism on our account, and it was just motivation for us to go harder and harder. Eventually, one game, it had to start." Marcel Jones scored 19 points and had 12 rebounds, including seven offensive boards, as Oregon State (9-9, 1-4 Pac-10) earned its first victory at Wells Fargo Arena since 1998. Both teams desperately wanted this game. They came in as the only remaining winless Pac-10 teams. Now only the Sun Devils (6-11, 0-6) can claim that distinction. With a young and inexperienced lineup, ASU knew it would struggle under new coach Herb Sendek. But this game loomed as perhaps the Sun Devils' best shot at a conference win. Instead, it became the seventh straight loss for the Sun Devils, who are off to their worst conference start since they lost their first seven games in 2000-01. Their next three games are at No. 4 UCLA, at USC and at No. 10 Arizona. The Sun Devils, who shot 35.4 percent from the floor and missed 14 straight shots in the final minutes, would have a hard time scoring against traffic cones. Jeff Pendergraph scored 19 points and pulled down 10 boards for ASU, which has scored in the 50s in four straight games. Banging away under the basket, Pendergraph hit 8-of-9 shots from the floor. His teammates made a combined 15-for-56 (26.7 percent). "Outside of Jeff Pendergraph, we continue to have a hard time doing what Dr. Naismith intended, and that's put the ball in the basket," Sendek said. "If you take (Pendergraph's) 8-for-9 away and do the math, that's a cold temperature we're living in." Sendek said his team's woes are no great mystery. "I don't see this as being Harry Potter," Sendek said. Indeed, there was little magic in this game. Both teams struggled to score, especially from long range. Oregon State shot 26.3 percent from 3-point range and ASU hit only 18.2 percent from beyond the arc. The Sun Devils led 33-27 at halftime, their first lead at intermission in eight games. The Sun Devils held the Beavers without a point for a span of 6:33 that ended early in the second half. But the Sun Devils couldn't put Oregon State away because they made only 2-of-18 shots from the floor during the same stretch. Arizona State missed 14 straight shots in the final minutes. Trailing 35-27 early in the second half, the Beavers went on a 13-4 run to take a 40-37 lead with 12:51 remaining. Arizona State tied the game at 42-42 on Pendergraph's basket with 9:26 to play, but the Beavers went on a 10-4 run to take their biggest lead at 52-46 with 5:07 remaining. From there, Oregon State held off the cold-shooting Sun Devils. The Beavers are the worst free-throw-shooting team in the league, averaging 62.5 percent from the line. But they hit 11-of-14 in the final 1:43 to wrap up the victory. It wasn't pretty, but it gave the Beavers a confidence boost as they headed home. They'll try to keep the momentum going against California and Stanford in Corallis next week. "I think it's extraordinarily important," Oregon State coach Jay John said. "They have been giving good effort, and they've stayed together and they've worked hard, and so they get a reward for this. We're going home for two (games), and there'll be a bit more bounce in their step, no question."
